01:21:03,439 --> 01:21:08,081
So we can look at the pictures of the letter against the wall and measure the height of the wall, and you get the height of the letter.

1081
01:21:09,641 --> 01:21:10,721
So there is work to be done.

1082
01:21:11,201 --> 01:21:19,064
I would just add an amendment that there is a neighborhood meeting before any RFPs go out, obviously, just for

1083
01:21:19,899 --> 01:21:24,820
I know you said the neighbors were very supportive of it, but we definitely want to get their input.

1084
01:21:25,261 --> 01:21:25,941
Oh, absolutely.

1085
01:21:26,321 --> 01:21:27,541
Again, it's a residential neighborhood.

1086
01:21:28,162 --> 01:21:31,242
So we don't want to put anything that anybody's going to have any objections with.

1087
01:21:32,003 --> 01:21:34,523
And it's not going to be lit at night all the time.

1088
01:21:35,244 --> 01:21:38,185
I mean, it's going to be lit probably during the day all day.

1089
01:21:39,065 --> 01:21:44,026
But at night, there's no point in really lighting it all night long, unless it's the night of the show.

1090
01:21:44,566 --> 01:21:45,987
And then, of course, it would be lit up.

1091
01:21:46,027 --> 01:21:49,548
So it wouldn't be something you'd be stuck blinking like a neon sign.

1092
01:21:50,330 --> 01:21:51,390
all night long in your window.

1093
01:21:52,091 --> 01:22:09,677
And then just another suggestion, when you look for input on, you know, a program that people would like to see, I know the paper is One Avenue and obviously the paper puts it online, but also social media, that can be huge, you know, getting the counselors involved and, you know, everybody's on Facebook nowadays.

1094
01:22:09,757 --> 01:22:17,760
I mean, I would really get input from all generations and maybe try to— There's no age limit on the input, you know.

1095
01:22:19,753 --> 01:22:25,895
If there's a, you can email the input to Chevalier Theatre or jcostas at chevaliertheatre.com.

1096
01:22:26,575 --> 01:22:29,196
And I think that'll be in the newspaper also.

1097
01:22:29,236 --> 01:22:37,659
So it's letter jcostas, C-O-S-T-A-S, at chevaliertheatre.com.

1098
01:22:37,879 --> 01:22:38,139
Ari.

1099
01:22:40,140 --> 01:22:46,722
I mean, we have such a population of families and just the younger generation too, which would,

1100
01:22:47,668 --> 01:22:56,772
I know you've spoken in subcommittee meetings just because people have requested that before, programming for children where families can go on a Saturday afternoon.

1101
01:22:56,832 --> 01:23:01,154
Even as simple as putting up a movie screen and watching a movie with popcorn with your kids.

1102
01:23:01,214 --> 01:23:07,057
I think that a couple bucks a person, there's so many different things you could.

1103
01:23:07,578 --> 01:23:08,739
the community can come up with.

1104
01:23:08,759 --> 01:23:12,961
So I think that getting the input is great and hopefully we can, Council can help in any way we can.

1105
01:23:13,001 --> 01:23:18,823
I mean, we requested this before and we got some input, but maybe that was four or five years ago and times have changed.

1106
01:23:18,863 --> 01:23:21,405
We've got new people in the city, new families coming in the city.

1107
01:23:21,425 --> 01:23:24,006
So we may get some great ideas that we didn't know about.

1108
01:23:24,026 --> 01:23:32,690
We should take that picture and then start the ad with that because I think that people would be amazed at how that looked and maybe people would spark an interest.

1109
01:23:33,510 --> 01:23:33,931
We can hope.

1110
01:23:33,951 --> 01:23:36,212
Thank you.

1111
01:23:39,749 --> 01:23:40,649
A quick question, John.

1112
01:23:42,150 --> 01:23:50,977
You had indicated some time back that the City of Lynn, I believe, fronts shows with money and the shows produce the money back.

1113
01:23:51,577 --> 01:23:51,777
Yes.

1114
01:23:51,997 --> 01:23:52,638
To the community.

1115
01:23:53,718 --> 01:23:54,299
I did say that.

1116
01:23:55,400 --> 01:23:57,401
Has the City of Medford ever offered that to you folks?

1117
01:23:59,202 --> 01:23:59,403
No.

1118
01:24:00,663 --> 01:24:02,745
Well, the mayor at one time did offer

1119
01:24:03,654 --> 01:24:07,535
to help do a revolving fund to fund shows.

1120
01:24:08,676 --> 01:24:12,857
But the problem with doing shows is that there is no winner.

1121
01:24:12,997 --> 01:24:14,958
I mean, you never know what the show is going to do.

1122
01:24:14,998 --> 01:24:16,099
You don't know if it's going to make money.

1123
01:24:16,119 --> 01:24:16,999
It's going to lose money.

1124
01:24:18,520 --> 01:24:22,001
What Lynn did is they went through a series of shows where they lost money.

1125
01:24:22,421 --> 01:24:25,202
But eventually, it turns around.

1126
01:24:25,442 --> 01:24:30,864
Because once you get the name out there and the shows are out there, they kind of just snowball.

1127
01:24:31,784 --> 01:24:33,245
And then they start investing some

1128
01:24:33,664 --> 01:24:34,044
more money.

1129
01:24:34,325 --> 01:24:41,390
So for example, our smaller shows, though, like we had John Denver last Friday night, it was a great show.

1130
01:24:41,410 --> 01:24:48,156
We had over 300 people in attendance, but it's very tough to make budget when you don't have sponsorships.

1131
01:24:49,056 --> 01:24:50,438
The budget of that show was around $15,000.

1132
01:24:50,558 --> 01:24:57,803
It's not an expensive show to do, but because of the type of show it is, it doesn't attract 1,000 people.

1133
01:24:58,884 --> 01:24:59,785
If we bring in a $100,000 show,

1134
01:25:01,836 --> 01:25:06,478
we're more likely to make a budget of $100,000 show if you brought in Natalie Cole.

1135
01:25:07,678 --> 01:25:15,361
So how could you make your argument successful for the city administration to front the money up front to get repaid back?

1136
01:25:15,622 --> 01:25:19,363
And there might be some losses in the beginning, like you said, until it gets to the point that it's repaid.

1137
01:25:19,383 --> 01:25:21,404
Well, it's called the investment.

1138
01:25:22,064 --> 01:25:31,548
And at one time at the city council, when we have the live shows, for example, Rick Springfield, financially, I think we lost five grand, but the hotel was packed.

1139
01:25:32,214 --> 01:25:36,476
So the city of Method made thousands of dollars in hotel tax.

1140
01:25:36,616 --> 01:25:42,759
Every time we have a show at the theater, Carol's, the Chinese, the Blue Fuji, Salvatore's, they're packed.

1141
01:25:43,399 --> 01:25:47,661
So $1,000, you know, more money in taxes, the meal tax.

1142
01:25:48,562 --> 01:25:53,824
And the way Lynn looks at it, and even lower, is that it's not a loss, it's an investment.

1143
01:25:53,844 --> 01:25:59,007
Because if you lose a million dollars here, but you gain four or five million dollars in revenue to the city,

1144
01:25:59,771 --> 01:26:06,314
The city gains, because obviously if somebody wants to be in business, to have a restaurant, you can increase property tax.

1145
01:26:06,355 --> 01:26:07,735
So everybody is a winner.

1146
01:26:08,035 --> 01:26:10,517
So you can't look at it so much as a loss.

1147
01:26:11,257 --> 01:26:20,342
Because yes, we may take a loss, but if we lose $5,000 and the city makes $10,000 on taxes, on hotel tax, we win.

1148
01:26:21,663 --> 01:26:24,264
If Carroll's and Salvatore's, same thing.

1149
01:26:25,218 --> 01:26:28,981
So my argument to you is, yes, we'll lose money, but we win.

1150
01:26:29,461 --> 01:26:31,302
We'll make money.

1151
01:26:31,342 --> 01:26:32,143
We're not really losing.

1152
01:26:32,183 --> 01:26:33,203
We can win in the long run.

1153
01:26:33,523 --> 01:26:39,668
Well, eventually, if we have enough, well, like, for example, Stoneham Theatre does really well.

1154
01:26:40,348 --> 01:26:43,130
But they have a mailing list of probably 5,000, 10,000.

1155
01:26:44,491 --> 01:26:46,272
We don't have a mailing list that large yet.

1156
01:26:47,172 --> 01:26:50,915
But every time we do shows, we add another 200 or 300 people to our mailing list.

1157
01:26:52,803 --> 01:26:55,544
I think everybody's on the mailing list and you all get the emails.

1158
01:26:56,185 --> 01:27:00,427
I think we have 2,500 emails now and every show we generate more emails.

1159
01:27:00,487 --> 01:27:07,490
So the more shows we do, the more interest we can generate, the more people we can have access to because they're on our mailing list.

1160
01:27:08,690 --> 01:27:14,153
You know, real quick, you just mentioned the Stoneham theater and you know yourself, they were struggling in the beginning to get themselves going.

1161
01:27:14,553 --> 01:27:18,155
And it was the type of shows that they brought in that's basically saved them.

1162
01:27:18,215 --> 01:27:18,775
And now they're,

1163
01:27:19,258 --> 01:27:20,499
They're for profit.

1164
01:27:20,699 --> 01:27:21,260
They're doing well.

1165
01:27:21,280 --> 01:27:22,201
They're doing really well.

1166
01:27:22,301 --> 01:27:24,022
And so isn't the region in Arlington.

1167
01:27:24,503 --> 01:27:24,883
Same thing.

1168
01:27:24,903 --> 01:27:27,445
They're a smaller theater, self-promoting theater.

1169
01:27:28,586 --> 01:27:28,906
Thank you.

1170
01:27:29,367 --> 01:27:29,667
Thank you.

1171
01:27:34,831 --> 01:27:36,733
Ma'am, please state your name and address for the record.

1172
01:27:40,528 --> 01:27:43,711
My marquee work at 16 Glenwood Ave, Medford, Mass.

1173
01:27:45,372 --> 01:27:53,379
I've been on the board of directors of the Friends of Chevalier for 22 years, a little bit longer than my age.

1174
01:27:54,520 --> 01:28:01,445
And I've been on the board of the Chevalier Theatre, organ society, since its inception, which I think was about 15 years ago.

1175
01:28:05,429 --> 01:28:09,512
I would like to thank Councilor Carviello for introducing the proposition

1176
01:28:11,071 --> 01:28:14,133
to install a marquee at the Chevalier Theatre.

1177
01:28:15,194 --> 01:28:25,863
Because I'm always pleased when this subject is on the council agenda, because it provides an opportunity for public conversation.

1178
01:28:28,625 --> 01:28:37,352
And I am definitely in favor of your support and recommendations to enhance the theatre with a marquee.

1179
01:28:38,713 --> 01:28:41,834
that would be an attractive and visible improvement on the building.

1180
01:28:42,835 --> 01:28:54,039
We still have people living in the city, especially new families, for which there are very, very many coming into the community in the last few years, who have no idea what's in that building.

1181
01:28:56,240 --> 01:29:05,463
And over the years, I have participated in many discussions about the Chevalier Theatre.

1182
01:29:06,303 --> 01:29:07,644
I've written many stories.

1183
01:29:08,495 --> 01:29:10,936
press releases, newsletters.

1184
01:29:12,956 --> 01:29:37,481
My basic concern is that even though the building is owned by the city of Medford and many, many and costly studies have been conducted that have consistently said the Chevalier Theatre has the potential of being a destination in the city and creating a vibrant district

1185
01:29:39,200 --> 01:29:44,042
that's pedestrian-friendly and attractive for downtown businesses.

1186
01:29:47,884 --> 01:29:55,387
The most recent study was the Sasaki Master Plan, which was issued in December of 2004.

1187
01:29:59,889 --> 01:30:07,612
I guess that's sitting someplace here at City Hall on a shelf, collecting dust, along with the other studies.

1188
01:30:09,670 --> 01:30:18,876
Because unfortunately, the recommendations that came out of that study and the previous studies have all fallen on deaf ears.

1189
01:30:22,399 --> 01:30:33,627
Why is taxpayer money being spent over and over again for these studies, but the citizens are not seeing any results?

1190
01:30:36,549 --> 01:30:38,410
We're all aware that in this past year,

1191
01:30:39,677 --> 01:30:46,362
Medford has been considered a very hot in the real estate market.

1192
01:30:47,322 --> 01:30:51,045
And as a result, it has received a lot of positive publicity.

1193
01:30:52,405 --> 01:30:59,810
Many young people, families, small children, professionals are moving into Medford.

1194
01:31:01,932 --> 01:31:08,916
These new residents are looking for a community offering good schools, transportation,

1195
01:31:09,521 --> 01:31:16,505
open space, safe neighborhoods, arts and cultural programs, to mention a few.

1196
01:31:17,626 --> 01:31:19,587
In short, a quality of life.

1197
01:31:22,669 --> 01:31:30,054
We have many assets here in Medford that other communities do not have, and the Chevalier Theater is one of them.

1198
01:31:31,215 --> 01:31:37,939
In addition, we have our history, the Mystic River, open space, just to mention a few,

1199
01:31:40,069 --> 01:31:44,271
But I feel that the city needs to do a better job in marketing itself.

1200
01:31:46,532 --> 01:32:08,544
As an advocate of the theater for more than 20 years, it has been obvious to me and many other residents that while the Chevalier has undergone major renovations, at the cost of probably $3.5 to $4 million, which has come from both private and public money,

1201
01:32:10,670 --> 01:32:21,679
And in addition, as well as the money, hundreds of volunteer hours by the Chevalier Auditorium Commission and the Friends of Chevalier.

1202
01:32:23,060 --> 01:32:25,042
It has not had a return on that investment.

1203
01:32:29,525 --> 01:32:39,013
There have been people who have been very, very faithful and supportive of the Chevalier Theatre for many, many years, and I would like to

1204
01:32:39,911 --> 01:32:50,115
publicly thank John Costas, who has been with this effort since the very beginning, and the late Geraldine Grandy and Dick Oba.

1205
01:32:51,435 --> 01:33:02,320
If it were not for those three people, possibly the Chevalier Theater may have become a parking lot, which would have been disastrous.

1206
01:33:04,841 --> 01:33:08,042
I would also like to make a few more observations.

1207
01:33:10,047 --> 01:33:38,840
The commission of five volunteers, in my opinion, should not be expected to manage the theater, oversee major renovations, raise funds for physical improvements to the building, which of course belongs to the city of Medford, and essentially do everything that is needed to make it successful with very, very little support from the city.

1208
01:33:40,320 --> 01:33:46,964
The commission has done an extraordinary job in bringing Chevalier to the level of a first class facility.

1209
01:33:49,286 --> 01:33:57,111
Recently, here in March, we observed the 75th anniversary concert.

1210
01:33:57,591 --> 01:34:01,054
We had a concert, which was very successful.

1211
01:34:02,715 --> 01:34:04,876
It came on the heels of 108 inches of snow.

1212
01:34:07,008 --> 01:34:12,569
And it was really a wonderful occasion, a great coming together of the community.

1213
01:34:13,449 --> 01:34:31,073
And many people who came there, because it was somewhat of a different show and it drew a different audience, they were amazed to learn of its existence in the first place and how magnificent the theater is, especially the acoustics,

1214
01:34:32,923 --> 01:34:36,885
the elliptical ceiling, and the unobstructed view of the stage.

1215
01:34:39,907 --> 01:35:00,858
Secondly, the commissioners do not receive stipends or other benefits, except for providing annual fuel assistance in the winter, which amounts to about $48,000, and occasional emergency funds when a piece of the building is falling off.

1216
01:35:03,011 --> 01:35:10,535
The city has not demonstrated interest in the potential of the theater as an engine for economic stimulus in Medford Square.

1217
01:35:12,256 --> 01:35:14,877
The city budget is about $145 million.

1218
01:35:14,897 --> 01:35:15,238
$145 million.

1219
01:35:15,258 --> 01:35:19,460
Why can't we allocate more than, and this figure is not even

1220
01:35:32,958 --> 01:35:43,605
1% or half a percent, it's .0003% of the budget for the theater.

1221
01:35:46,007 --> 01:35:51,550
There has to be a few dollars somewhere that can be allocated for Chevalier.

1222
01:35:53,131 --> 01:35:56,774
The demographics and diversity of Medford are changing rapidly.

1223
01:35:57,714 --> 01:35:58,495
We all know that.

1224
01:36:00,457 --> 01:36:05,398
and residents are welcoming a growing arts and cultural movement in the city.

1225
01:36:06,858 --> 01:36:19,921
Today, with the population that we have and the diversity that we have in the community, there is a greater range of artistic talent to share with all our residents in Medford and beyond.

1226
01:36:23,342 --> 01:36:28,883
Unfortunately, arts and culture

1227
01:36:29,566 --> 01:36:32,747
are often thought of as frivolous and unessential.

1228
01:36:34,648 --> 01:36:36,228
This is not true.

1229
01:36:37,488 --> 01:36:43,770
Studies are emerging that are quantifying the value of arts and culture to a community.

1230
01:36:45,431 --> 01:36:58,515
In June of 2004, a report titled The Arts Factor concluded that arts and culture are as essential and fundamental to our identity as the American Revolution

1231
01:37:00,829 --> 01:37:13,812
that innovative and inspiring cities place arts and culture among their greatest assets, and that arts and culture is an economic engine for the community.

1232
01:37:16,113 --> 01:37:21,054
I am in favor, and thank you, Councilor Carviello, for your proposal.

1233
01:37:22,514 --> 01:37:30,096
However, I would like to say that without the support of the city, and without a vision or a plan,

1234
01:37:31,427 --> 01:37:38,990
for the future of Chevalier, which this council can very, very well initiate and participate in.

1235
01:37:40,651 --> 01:37:42,231
We are in a cycle of going nowhere.

1236
01:37:44,112 --> 01:37:47,173
Change in our community is blowing in the wind.

1237
01:37:49,834 --> 01:37:53,696
And we all need to work together to meet tomorrow's challenges.

1238
01:37:54,376 --> 01:37:54,736
Thank you.

1239
01:38:00,259 --> 01:38:00,959
Thank you, Mr. President.

1240
01:38:01,242 --> 01:38:02,422
You know, May, I agree with you 100%.

1241
01:38:02,542 --> 01:38:06,263
You know, the people in this community are changing.

1242
01:38:06,283 --> 01:38:08,984
There's more and more younger families that have moved here.

1243
01:38:09,004 --> 01:38:09,644
And you're right.

1244
01:38:10,264 --> 01:38:13,345
There's hundreds of many families that have no idea what goes on in that building.

1245
01:38:13,365 --> 01:38:18,606
You know, every morning, if you go down Forest Street, the traffic is backed up to 93.

1246
01:38:18,966 --> 01:38:24,387
That would pay for itself just in advertising alone, that people would get to see that.

1247
01:38:24,447 --> 01:38:29,249
As I say, there's cars that are there that sit at Forest Street for an hour, cutting through to go.

1248
01:38:31,575 --> 01:38:39,540
And I would hope that the new administration coming into this building next year will see the benefit of that building.

1249
01:38:40,420 --> 01:38:47,745
And I say, I mean, all one has to do is pick up the newspaper and see the lineup that Lynn puts out every year.

1250
01:38:47,765 --> 01:38:49,346
I mean, every week and every month.

1251
01:38:50,347 --> 01:38:53,408
And I talk to people, why can't we have that here?

1252
01:38:53,789 --> 01:38:57,011
There's no reason why we can't get some of the talent that Lynn gets.

1253
01:38:58,351 --> 01:39:00,833
I mean, they had Natalie Cole there not too long ago.

1254
01:39:01,513 --> 01:39:04,534
I mean, there's a woman who has Medford roots.

1255
01:39:05,254 --> 01:39:07,275
No reason why we couldn't have had her.

1256
01:39:07,315 --> 01:39:15,937
I mean, State Representative Donato went and got state funding for all the new seats in that building that don't get the use that they should be.

1257
01:39:16,257 --> 01:39:18,338
Those seats should be worn out from all the people going in there.

1258
01:39:18,998 --> 01:39:23,039
And the other thing that that building lacks, the building should have a concession stand.

1259
01:39:24,359 --> 01:39:29,141
That would be a major generator of money for that building if they had a full-time concession stand.

1260
01:39:29,161 --> 01:39:30,441
So every time you have an event there,

1261
01:39:31,368 --> 01:39:33,610
You'd make money on your whatever you happen to sell there.

1262
01:39:34,570 --> 01:39:35,351
That's all profit.

1263
01:39:36,312 --> 01:39:42,796
So again, I would hope that the new administration takes a different view than the past administration has in that building.

1264
01:39:46,419 --> 01:39:46,819
Thank you.

1265
01:39:46,919 --> 01:39:59,088
And, um, you know, I, I certainly support this this evening, but, um, I think this council has been very supportive of the arts, uh, just within the last few years, the line item that was offered by counselor marks.

1266
01:39:59,683 --> 01:40:01,964
for arts in our community was put into the budget.

1267
01:40:01,984 --> 01:40:04,065
I believe it was $25,000 at the time.

1268
01:40:04,686 --> 01:40:09,388
And it's something that we've made sure that it was put in year after year.

1269
01:40:09,909 --> 01:40:11,650
Now, I look back a few years ago.

1270
01:40:11,670 --> 01:40:11,650
$15,000?

1271
01:40:12,670 --> 01:40:13,571
OK.

1272
01:40:14,491 --> 01:40:20,194
I look back a few years ago, and at the time, it was President Stephanie Muccini-Burke who was the chairperson of the council.

1273
01:40:20,614 --> 01:40:23,796
And we did have a proposal for an art center here in our community.

1274
01:40:24,777 --> 01:40:28,859
And the only three councilors at the time that supported it, for whatever reason,

