2347
03:00:37,206 --> 03:00:39,208
What is the kind of world that other people would like to live in?

2348
03:00:39,708 --> 03:00:45,754
And it seems to me that the way that our political process goes today is just, in our city at least, we vote once a year.

2349
03:00:46,962 --> 03:00:51,624
And the options are very, they're very slim about, I mean, what we can vote about.

2350
03:00:52,064 --> 03:00:55,865
So I was really happy to find out last year about something called participatory budgeting.

2351
03:00:55,885 --> 03:00:58,426
It started in Brazil in 1989.

2352
03:00:59,606 --> 03:01:02,347
And it's spread to 1,500 countries around the world.

2353
03:01:02,807 --> 03:01:09,990
What it's really about is people, just citizens or residents, being able to vote on where money will be allocated to.

2354
03:01:10,410 --> 03:01:12,531
Now, it's only really a very small amount.

2355
03:01:14,071 --> 03:01:18,375
It's not for operating expenses, more for capital expenses.

2356
03:01:18,716 --> 03:01:22,279
So these are projects that should be implemented within one year.

2357
03:01:22,299 --> 03:01:30,347
And it's also just not excluded to people who have registered through the traditional process.

2358
03:01:30,407 --> 03:01:31,828
It's open to anybody who's a resident.

2359
03:01:32,189 --> 03:01:36,213
So frequently this includes students as well as schools up to sometimes 12 years old.

2360
03:01:36,946 --> 03:01:43,870
Um, I spoke to Michael Marx last year about this, or actually a few months ago, and I wanted to know how the process would go.

2361
03:01:43,950 --> 03:01:45,230
And he said I should speak to the mayor.

2362
03:01:45,851 --> 03:01:49,352
But, um, you know, then the mayor announced that he's resigning.

2363
03:01:49,772 --> 03:01:51,974
So I figured that I should speak to Stephanie Burke.

2364
03:01:54,115 --> 03:01:55,335
He's not running for reelection.

2365
03:01:56,396 --> 03:01:57,096
Yes, I'm sorry.

2366
03:01:58,737 --> 03:01:59,157
Excuse me.

2367
03:01:59,177 --> 03:01:59,517
Thank you.

2368
03:01:59,838 --> 03:02:00,598
Thank you for the correction.

2369
03:02:01,225 --> 03:02:04,290
So I was thinking it would be reasonable to speak to Stephanie Burke.

2370
03:02:04,730 --> 03:02:10,298
So I went to her office last year and I figured because she's the budget director and she may be our next mayor.

2371
03:02:11,179 --> 03:02:17,448
But I was told by one of her assistants that she doesn't really do that when I asked to have an appointment with her.

2372
03:02:18,276 --> 03:02:20,617
Um, which is, is, is really unfortunate.

2373
03:02:20,837 --> 03:02:25,440
Um, but, um, yesterday I did speak to one of the budget analysts from Cambridge.

2374
03:02:26,020 --> 03:02:27,881
And we spoke on the telephone for half an hour.

2375
03:02:28,322 --> 03:02:31,903
And she was part in rolling out participatory budgeting in, in Cambridge.

2376
03:02:32,564 --> 03:02:35,085
And she told me just so much about how the process works.

2377
03:02:35,726 --> 03:02:40,048
Um, what they did is one of the city councilors in November recommended that, um,

2378
03:02:40,505 --> 03:02:42,406
They consider participatory budgeting.

2379
03:02:42,746 --> 03:02:48,990
And they did this very intense process of going to the schools and the community centers and taking so many ideas from people.

2380
03:02:49,190 --> 03:02:54,013
They even put this thing on the website where people can say where they want projects to be done.

2381
03:02:54,814 --> 03:02:57,816
And they took input from a lot of people as well as meetings.

2382
03:02:58,196 --> 03:03:02,378
So they started by asking for volunteers to be part of a steering committee that was 22 people.

2383
03:03:03,739 --> 03:03:09,743
And then the steering committee basically had to make certain determinations about all the logistics, like how much it would cost.

2384
03:03:10,370 --> 03:03:19,157
You know, and after they did some of the big main decisions, then they just made determinations.

2385
03:03:19,197 --> 03:03:23,861
They broke them into four budget delegate committees based on what kind of a project was.

2386
03:03:24,462 --> 03:03:30,086
And what they eventually got were 380 submissions from all the different citizens of Cambridge.

2387
03:03:31,828 --> 03:03:36,571
And over months and months of this process and people voting and a lot of input,

2388
03:03:37,697 --> 03:03:41,500
they brought it down to 30, because each committee can say whether or not it's applicable.

2389
03:03:42,160 --> 03:03:47,464
Like there's a Parks and Recreations Committee, and then there's a Streets and Sidewalks Committee.

2390
03:03:48,685 --> 03:03:59,713
And so after they brought it down to 30, 30 options for people to vote on out of 380, then it went to the city manager, and they took a look at how much each one of the things would cost.

2391
03:04:00,798 --> 03:04:02,960
and what could actually be done.

2392
03:04:02,980 --> 03:04:09,247
And they also actually have to look at what was already in the city's budget, you know, so that there's no overlap.

2393
03:04:10,528 --> 03:04:16,714
But one of the things that's really wonderful about processes like this is that they increase citizen engagement.

2394
03:04:17,575 --> 03:04:23,121
And time and time again, more people get involved in this process than actually do in voting.

2395
03:04:23,510 --> 03:04:27,153
Now, a lot of that is because these elections are done online.

2396
03:04:28,154 --> 03:04:35,080
And in a city like ours, I don't have any delusions that we'd be able to roll out an election on our city website.

2397
03:04:35,781 --> 03:04:42,307
However, it does bring a lot of people involved in these meetings who had never really ever considered having input.

2398
03:04:43,654 --> 03:04:46,660
about where money should be spent in the city.

2399
03:04:47,441 --> 03:04:54,775
And there is a lot of discussion about things that aren't working in our city, about things that need to be repaired here and here, but a lot of times it's just a sole voice.

2400
03:04:55,669 --> 03:05:02,453
